you can try to brute force it using john --format=lm hashes.txt, but this will take a long time
instead, we can reduce the keyspace using a technique known as masking
Keyspace refers to the number of possible combinations at a given length. 
Can be calculated using taking the number of different characters to the power of the length of the password.
example, a password using only numbers upper case letters 5 characters long can be represented as (10+26)^5, or 
60,466,176 possible combinations.

Windows legacy password hash has a few weaknesses we can use to limit our keyspace,
1. It caps password length at 7 characters
2. All lowercase characters are converted to upper case
3. A secret 3rd thing, I have it on good authority that 2nd character is either a special character or an upper case letter.

john --format=1m -1=?u?d?s -2=?u?s --mask=?1?2?1?1?1?1?1 --min-length=3 --max-length=7 trimmed.txt
